        "id": "fn-web-extension-jerusalem-s-destruction-exile-from-palestine-the-subsequent-history-of-christianity-judaism-89",
        "number": 89,
        "displayNumber": 89,
        "markerKey": "web-extension-jerusalem-s-destruction-exile-from-palestine-the-subsequent-history-of-christianity-judaism:web-extension:89",
        "origin": "web-extension",
        "content": "<p> <strong>The Elkesaites </strong>(Greek: <em>Elkesaî</em>, <em>Ελκεσαΐ</em>  and <em>Ēlkesaî</em>, <em>Ἠλχασαΐ</em>) were an ancient Judeo-Christian sect that originated in Palestine but appeared primarily in Southern Mesopotamia (present-day Iraq) during the reign of Emperor Trajan (d. 117 CE) and who were active from about 100 CE until 400 CE. Their name probably comes from the Hebrew-Aramaic “Hidden God” (<em>Ēl Kesî</em>) “hidden God” or “Hidden Power” (<em>Ḥîl Kesî</em>). In converting non-Jews, the Elkesaites required that the proselyte first embrace Judaism. They performed frequent and repeated Baptisms for purification. In Arabic, they are called “the Ritual Washers” (<em>al-Mughtasila</em>). Baptism among the Elkesaites was performed by the immersion of the entire body while dressed in a garment in a river or spring. In Mesopotamia, they sometimes baptized their believers in the Euphrates River. In their belief, such baptism brought divine remission of sins. It was performed in the name of the “Great and most High God” and combined with His adoration. Before baptism, the believer had to declare that he or she would abstain from all sin and all improbity in conduct. They also used baptism as treatment for diseases, poisons, and venom. They may also have sanctioned a type of Eucharist with bread and salt. The Elkesaites required circumcision, observance of the Sabbath, and adherence to the Law of Moses. The Elkesaites taught the remission of sins and held a dualistic orientation similar to the Christian Gnostics, who had first appeared but been checked in the days of the Jerusalem Church but began to flourish again in the days of Trajan. The Elkesaites sanctioned marriage and forbad eating meat, although the prohibition may well have been restricted to the meat offered in Pagan sacrificial meals. They believed in One God and the Last Judgment and insisted that the believers turn toward Jerusalem in prayer, while forbidding the custom of praying toward the East.  </p>",
        "sectionId": "web-extension-jerusalem-s-destruction-exile-from-palestine-the-subsequent-history-of-christianity-judaism"
